## Recommended: Adopt `System.IO.Abstractions`

This is a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps the entire `System.IO` surface — no need to write custom interfaces.

**1. Install the package:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI:**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class ConfigService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool FolderExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});
var service = new ConfigService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/data/config.json"));

service.Save("/data/output.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/output.txt"));

Assert.True(service.FolderExists("/data"));
Assert.False(service.FolderExists("/missing"));
```

---

**Why this over a custom wrapper?**
- Covers `File.*`, `Directory.*`, `Path.*`, `DriveInfo`, etc. — one package for all of `System.IO`
- `MockFileSystem` provides an in-memory filesystem out of the box (no mocking library needed)
- Maintained, widely used, and tracks new .NET APIs

Once you've added the package and DI registration, replace each `File.ReadAllText(...)` call site with `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(...)` (and similarly for the others). If you have many call sites to migrate, I can help with that too — just point me at the project.
